      "content": "### 2) REASON: why these features affect CYP2D6 inhibition\n- **Cationic/basic center:** CYP2D6 inhibitors commonly have a **protonatable N** that can form a strong ionic interaction with the enzyme\u2019s acidic residue (classically Asp in the binding site). A **tertiary amine** is a strong match.\n- **Aromatic/lipophilic bulk:** CYP2D6 binding pockets favor **hydrophobic and aromatic interactions**; having **two aromatic systems** plus a conjugated linker increases the chance of tight binding and competitive inhibition.\n- **Geometry/distance:** The tertiary amine is **directly attached to an aromatic ring**, and the molecule extends into another aromatic heterocycle through a **styryl linker**\u2014a common arrangement for CYP2D6 inhibitors where the basic center anchors and the aromatic system occupies hydrophobic regions.",
